Me in 2014, shooting in my first New York apartment. I didn’t have any equipment or lighting at this time. I had a pull out sofa bed, and would fold it up so I could shoot portraits of models in the corner next to my window. This is how I learned to shape and understand light. These were all done for free so I could build a portfolio. After a while, one of the agencies began paying me $150 per shoot and I did as many as I could. 

Back then, all I could think about was my fear of not being able to turn photography into a livable career and how I had no back up plan. I wish I’d been a bit more present and enjoyed the experiences. That being said, the best part was how I met new models from all over the world. It was usually a one on one shoot, which was super intimate and led to amazing conversations. 🖤

2022 was full of more amazing experiences, opportunities and growth than I could have imagined. A huge thank to to everyone who supported and collaborated with me this year. I feel like I really started to find my voice over these last 12 months. Can’t wait to see what next year brings. 🥂
I don’t think I can narrow down 2022 to just 10 pictures, but these were definitely some highlights 🫶 Thank you thank you thank you to everyone for such an amazing year ❤️

Last one 🫶 but thanks to everyone for supporting and collaborating with me this year. I really couldn’t have done it without the photo assistants, digi techs, and producers who helped me on set. One of my favorite parts of December is always to sit down, take a look through everything I created over 12 months, and think about all of the people I met. Everything is so fast pasted these days with content creation and speeding out results that I rarely take a moment to breathe and enjoy the process. No matter how much I shoot, it never feels like enough in this day and age. It feels corny to say but I’m aiming to be more ‘in the moment’ next year. 🤍

It’s the holidays and I’m feeling extra grateful that I get to be a full time photographer ❤️ I’ve opened up about this before so it may be repetitive for some, but I dropped out of high school due to bullying and was too nervous to go to college after. I’ve spent 12 years building my portfolio and skills. It’s just in the last year or so that I feel like I’ve found my voice as an artist. Be patient with your journey.

I’ve been receiving a lot of questions lately asking if I create background colors in post. Nope, they are all shot in camera!

Every year when Pride Month comes around, I experience a lot of emotions. I always think back to when I first moved to New York 12 years ago. I was 16 and arrived during June. I left school due to bullying and not feeling safe because of my queer identity. It was a strange experience the move to NYC and have the Pride parade go right by my apartment. What was meant to be something that should only bring anyone pride, love and joy - made me feel confused and anxious. For so long what many had made me feel was was wrong with me was being embraced and celebrated? It was hard to process. Over the next few years, I navigated what being gay meant to me. I’m now 28, and while there is still a lot that I’m always learning and navigating - I’ve made so much progress. It makes me proud to think how far I’ve come from being that scared teenage boy. 

I’ve been really fortunate over the last few years to get to work with some incredible LGBTQIA+ individuals who are making an impact for the community and are also fantastic role models. Growing up, and even in my early 20’s, I can only think of a handful of names that were queer representation in the media. It feels really special to get to contribute to this - even in a small way - to help showcase these amazing people and see the images circulate out in the world. A big thank you to the photo editors and clients for many of these projects, and of course the lovely people I’ve gotten to photograph. Here’s to many more. 🌈 🥂

In order of appearance: Zane Phillips, Ben Aldridge, Jim Parsons, Jeremy Pope, Luke Evans, Ariana DeBose, Bowen Yang, Jinkx Monsoon, Connor Jessup, Shaun Ross and Tan France.

Starting off my summer go sees series with the lovely @sallycarolinebloom. I very rarely have the chance to take photos one on one, and as much as I love creating with teams - I thought it would be fun to shoot a project that reminded me of when I was starting out. 

I used to take the train into NY after school to meet up with people on the street and walk around photographing them. They would change outfits in public restrooms, coffee shops, alleyways, etc. The chaos of it was super fun - and I got to meet so many incredible people that came from all over the world to take a stab at modeling. 

In 2017, I joined my first photo studio share - and would have 3-5 models stop by a day to experiment and have fun with photography. This was when I discovered how much I loved shooting studio work - it was a way I could really focus on highlighting the individual in a more controlled environment. 

While these images feel very simplistic, I think it’s going to be a lot of fun to compare them to when I was shooting with a similar approach years ago and see where my work has grown.

Two years ago, this week, I was featured on @abcnews by the incredible @sandykenyon7. Sandy has been beyond supportive since I began my career in photography. He first found my work online in 2011, when I was sixteen, and did a feature that really helped give me the confidence and support I needed to start pursuing things full time. 

A few years later, also this week (but in 2016), Sandy did a follow up feature to document my ventures and how they were progressing. This was at a time where I was just starting to “break in” to the industry and majorly dealing with imposter syndrome, so to receive this positive highlight and encouragement meant so much. 

Then we have 2021, just following the insane whirlwind of the pandemic, and I’m getting back to work. Sandy comes back to me again - a third time - wanting to do a 10 year follow up piece showcasing where I’d landed in photography. To say that he has shown me SO much support over the years would be an understatement. So grateful for all of the experiences and memories. ❤️

Wrapping up 2023 with a little photo dump of memories and a few thoughts to go along with. 

To say this year was filled with ups and downs would be an understatement. One of the most important things I’ve learned is that there is no *right way* to do things, or *correct* career trajectory for a creative to follow. I’ve spent years comparing myself to others. At the end of the day, I feel best when I create the work that I’d like to create - and from there the rest has started to fall into place. 

Struggling with self confidence and imposter syndrome has always been a major issue for me - and I know a lot of other artists deal with this too. It sounds quite corny to write out, but learning to trust my gut - even with fear of following it - has been the best life lesson this year. You won’t always make the right decision, and that is okay. You will be okay. 

A very special thank you to all of the lovely souls I’ve gotten to meet and collaborate with this year - looking back there have been so many incredible experiences that I’ll cherish for a long time. Thank you to everyone who has supported me online as well, it means a lot. Excited for what 2024 will bring. 🥂
